{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522994"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:50:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13863"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13863"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.59,0.1,0.24,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52867"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6480"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38247"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"318"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15302"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52867"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of cough, fever, and progressive shortness of breath. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. Her regular medications include metformin and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 118/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, temperature 38.5\u00b0C, and oxygen saturation 92% on 2 L/min nasal prongs. Her mucous membranes are dry, and her skin turgor is decreased. She has not produced any urine in the last four hours. Appropriate intravenous fluid therapy is commenced immediately.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of blood test results is most likely given the patient\u0027s fluid status? (Reference ranges: Sodium 135-145 mmol/L, Potassium 3.5-5.0 mmol/L, Creatinine 60-110 \u00b5mol/L)","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sodium 135 mmol/L, Potassium 3.8 mmol/L, Creatinine 80 \u00b5mol/L","Sodium 148 mmol/L, Potassium 5.5 mmol/L, Creatinine 180 \u00b5mol/L","Sodium 128 mmol/L, Potassium 3.2 mmol/L, Creatinine 60 \u00b5mol/L","Sodium 145 mmol/L, Potassium 4.8 mmol/L, Creatinine 120 \u00b5mol/L","Sodium 142 mmol/L, Potassium 5.8 mmol/L, Creatinine 90 \u00b5mol/L"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s clinical presentation of shock, signs of significant fluid depletion and renal dysfunction, the most likely set of blood test results is \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium 148 mmol/L, Potassium 5.5 mmol/L, Creatinine 180 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/strong\u003E. This combination reflects the expected changes in a patient with severe dehydration and secondary renal dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe elevated sodium (148 mmol/L) suggests hypernatraemia, which is consistent with the patient\u0027s fluid deficit. The high potassium (5.5 mmol/L) could be due to a combination of factors including renal dysfunction, acidosis (common in shock), and the shift of potassium from intracellular to extracellular space in severe dehydration. The markedly elevated creatinine (180 \u00b5mol/L) indicates acute kidney injury, likely pre-renal due to hypoperfusion in the context of shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option with \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium 135 mmol/L, Potassium 3.8 mmol/L, Creatinine 80 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents normal values and does not reflect the patient\u0027s severe clinical state. These results might be seen in a well-hydrated individual without any significant medical issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, the set showing \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium 145 mmol/L, Potassium 4.8 mmol/L, Creatinine 120 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates high normal electrolyte concentrations with slightly elevated creatinine. While this might be seen in some cases of fluid depletion, it doesn\u0027t reflect the severity of this patient\u0027s condition. This pattern could be observed in a patient with mild to moderate dehydration, however would not be expected in a patient who is clinically oliguric or anuric, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option with \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium 142 mmol/L, Potassium 5.8 mmol/L, Creatinine 90 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents hyperkalaemia without renal dysfunction. While hyperkalaemia can occur in shock due to acidosis and cellular shifts, the normal creatinine is inconsistent with the patient\u0027s clinical picture of oliguria and severe dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe set showing \u003Cstrong\u003ESodium 128 mmol/L, Potassium 3.2 mmol/L, Creatinine 60 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/strong\u003E suggests hyponatraemia and hypokalaemia with normal renal function, which is inconsistent with the patient\u0027s presentation of severe dehydration and oliguria. This pattern could be seen in conditions such as SIADH (Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone secretion) or excessive fluid intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the combination of hypernatraemia, hyperkalaemia, and significantly elevated creatinine best represents the expected blood chemistry in a patient with severe dehydration and early renal dysfunction due to shock.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with shock, fluid status can be assessed through vital signs, physical examination findings, and blood chemistry review.","Multiple clinical parameters should be considered when evaluating fluid status, including mucous membranes, skin turgor, and presence of sweat and tears.","Blood chemistry review, including electrolytes, urea, and creatinine, provides crucial information about a patient\u0027s fluid and electrolyte balance."],"references":["Malbrain MLNG, Van Regenmortel N, Saugel B, De Tavernier B, Van Gaal P-J, Joannes-Boyau O, et al. Principles of fluid management and stewardship in septic shock: it is time to consider the four D\u2019s and the four phases of fluid therapy. Annals of Intensive Care. 2018;8(1):66. Available at: https://annalsofintensivecare.springeropen.com/articles/10.1186/s13613-018-0402-x","Choi HM, Kim SC, Kim MG, Jo SK, Cho WY, Kim HK. Etiology and outcomes of anuria in acute kidney injury: a single center study. Kidney Res Clin Pract. 2015 Mar;34(1):13-9. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4570603/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38247"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13863"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38247"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-11T10:06:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T10:07:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6480"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52867"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"typ